Multipliers capture the size of the secondary effects in a given region, generally as a ratio of the total change in economic activity in the region relative to the direct change. - http://corpslakes.usace.army.mil/employees/economic/glossary.html
Number or quantity that records a directly observable value or performance. All measures have a unit attached to them: inch, centimeter, dollar, liter, etc.

the maximum amount of any substance that can be safely ingested by a human. Ingestion that exceeds this amount may cause toxic effects. This term is usually applied to additives, residues, or chemicals not normally found in foods.
Elevation especially above sea level or above the earth's surface
The temperature at which a liquid boils at sea level
Density defined in a qualitative manner as the measure of the relative "heaviness" of objects with a constant volume.
The magnitude of something in a particular direction (especially length or width or height)
The level of pest infestation below which the cost of further reducing the pest population exceeds the additional revenue or value of other benefits such reduction would achieve.
the difference in electrical charge between two points in a circuit expressed in volts
The ratio of grain weight to total plant weight.
The potential of water molecules to move from a hypotonic solution (more water, less solutes) to a hypertonic solution (less water, more solutes) across a semi permeable membrane.
The logarithm of the reciprocal of hydrogen-ion concentration in gram atoms per liter; provides a measure on a scale from 0 to 14 of the acidity or alkalinity of a solution
The pH value of the dispersion medium of a colloidal suspension at which the colloidal particles do not move in an electric field.
The force applied to a unit area of surface; measured in pascals (SI unit) or in dynes (cgs unit)
The electrical potential associated with the oxidation and reduction of a substance suchas an element or molecule
The maximum amount of water that a particular soil can hold
The density of a substance relative to the density of water
Distance travelled per unit time
The difference in free energy or chemical potential (per unit molal volume) between pure water and water in cells and solutions.
The ratio of the volume of carbon dioxide expired to the volume of oxygen consumed by an organism or cell in a given period of time
Evapotranspiration (ET) is a term describing the transport of water into the atmosphere from surfaces, including soil (soil evaporation), and from vegetation (transpiration).

The temperature at which the pressure exerted by molecules leaving a liquid equals the pressure exerted by the molecules in the air above it. A free-for-all of molecules leaving the liquid then ensues.

a. The quantity of something per unit measure, especially per unit length, area, or volume. 
b. The mass per unit volume of a substance under specified conditions of pressure and temperature.
the temperature below which a liquid turns into a solid

measure of the ability of an insoluble material to undergo displacement of ions previously attached and loosely incorporated into its structure by oppositely charged ions present in the surrounding solution. Zeolite minerals used in water softening, for example, have a large capacity to exchange sodium ions (Na+) for calcium ions (Ca2+) of hard water. High cation-exchange capacities are characteristic of clay minerals and numerous other natural and synthetic substances possessing ion-exchanging properties.

Isoelectric point is the pH of a solution or dispersion at which the net charge on the macromolecules or colloidal particles is zero. In electrophoresis there is no motion of the particles in an electric field at the isoelectric point.

The temperature at which a solid turns into a liquid. As temperature is a measure of the kinetic energy of molecules (how much they are moving around), this means that the molecules are moving too much to stay in one place anymore.
The combined weight (as given on the periodic table) of all the elements in a compound. In chemistry the words mass and weight are both used interchageably
Negative logarithm of the concentration (mol/L) of the H3O+[H+] ion; scale is commonly used over a range 0 to 14.
The potential of a reversible oxidation-reduction electrode measured with respect to a reference electrode, corrected to the hydrogen electrode, in a given electrolyte.
the number of milligrams of potassium hydroxide (KOH) consumed in neutralizing and saponifying one gram of a product, under standardized conditions
The ratio of the density of a substance to the density of water.

The 'heaviness' of an object, the amount of attraction between two or more masses. Weight is often measured in Kilogrammes but the proper (SI) unit of weight is the Newton. Weight is not the same as mass which is a measure of how much matter or inertia an object has. Weight on the other hand is dependant on two or more masses and is a measure of the force of gravity acting on those two objects.
Surface runoff is the water flow that occurs when soil is infiltrated to full capacity and excess water from rain, snowmelt, or other sources flows over the land.
An index of the acidity or alkalinity of the soil.
the maximum amount of water that a particular soil can hold
the amount of water in a soil when a plant cannot obtain enough water to remain turgid.
the maximum number of organisms of a given species that can be supported in a given area or habitat.
The balance at any location between the input— precipitation, (P)—and the outputs: evapotranspiration (E) and run‐off (R):P = E + R.

The part of precipitation or irrigation water on land that has limited interaction with the landscape and ultimately reaches surface water, such as streams, ponds, impoundments, reservoirs, oceans, rivers, etc.

Subsurface runoff is the water that infiltrates in the vadose zone (unsaturated zone), from rain, snowmelt, or other sources, and moves laterally towards the streams. Vadose zone extends from the top of the ground surface to the water table.
The ratio of the volume of contained water in a soil compared with the entire soil volume.
The difference between the amount of water that is in a soil and the amount needed for crops to grow successfully.
It is an indication of the alkalinity or acidity of soil. It is based on the measurement of pH, which is based in turn on the concentration of hydrogen ions (H+) in a water or salt solution.
The temperature measured at a given soil depth, typically at 2, 4, 8, and sometimes 20 and 40 in.
The maximum possible amount of water remaining in the soil after excess water has drained away.
The soil water content below which plants wilt and are unable to recover.

Total soil water potential is defined as the amount of work per unit quantity of pure water that must be done by external forces to transfer reversibly and isothermally an infinitesimal amount of water from the standard state to the soil at the point under consideration.
The maximum number of livestock that can be supported in a given area.
When grain absorbs moisture, the percentage of moisture content is given as the weight of the grain when it is dry or when it is wet.
The work required to transfer a unit of positive electric charge from an infinite distance to a given point.
The temperature at which a liquid becomes solid.
Number of inorganic groups per specified amount of ion-exchanger.
A measure of the fertility of soil which describes its ability to hold and supply nutrients.
The total exchangeable anions that a soil can adsorb, measured as milliequivalents per 100 grams of soil.
The pH value at which there is no electric force on a molecule in a solution.
The rate of change of position in a given direction which is composed of both speed and direction.
The temperature at which a solid turns to liquid.
The sum of all the atomic weights of the atoms in a molecule.
The ratio of the speed of refracted light in a vacuum to its speed in the medium being studied.
A measure of the acidity of a solution, determined as the negative logarithm of the hydrogen ion concentration, on a scale from 0 to 14.
It is an indication of the alkalinity or acidity of soil.
A measure of the ability of the natural environment to bring about an oxidation or a reduction process.
The number of milligrams of potassium hydroxide required to saponify one gram of a given ester, esp. a glyceride.
A measurement of heat.
The measure of the level of heat of a human or animal.
The ratio of the heat energy absorbed by a substance to the substance's increase in temperature.
Territory may be viewed as the area where an individual or community lives.
